Hard drives have two kinds of components: internal and external.
External components are located on a printed circuit board called 
logic board while internal components are located in a sealed chamber
called HDA or Hard Drive Assembly.

Connectors

Hard disk drives have basically two connectors, one for power and
other for exchanging data with the computer. This second connector
is better known as “interface”. The most common hard disk drive 
interface for end-users is called ATA (Advanced Technology Attachment),
while SATA (Serial ATA) interface was created to replace ATA and is 
becoming more popular these days. After the released of SATA, ATA 
interface started being also called PATA (Parallel ATA). Another 
famous interface is called SCSI (Small Computer Systems Interface),
but it is targeted to servers and rarely seen on PCs targeted to end-users.

Logic Board

On the logic board you will find all circuitry in charge of controlling
the hard drive.




